an provide for her in the home and the community. &#10;@beautifulburnout, I'm afraid that they duty you describe the LA having does not exist in law. If the LA suspect the education is unsuitable they must of course pursue it - but parent's are not compelled to show work or accept home visits. They can show their provision in a number of other ways, and if the LA is unhappy with this they can issue a school attendance order. I couldn't/wouldn't show examples of DD's 'work' because we don't do any form of school at home and DD doesn't have 'work' to show that would satisfy someone used to a schooling model of education. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="926" language="en" documentId="1082" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="anastaisia" date="28 July 2010 10:58pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6870587" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="18" thumbsDown="0" origId="1082" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="7"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="8" end="353"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="354" end="926"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>